# Workflow Standards

## Atomic Changes (AC)
Make small, self-contained modifications for traceability and rollback.

## Commit Discipline (CD)
Use conventional commit format: type(scope): description
Types: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore

## Change Scope Discipline (CSD)
Only modify files directly related to the current task.
Never make unrelated "improvements" without explicit permission.

## Context Window Management (CWM)
- Be mindful of AI context limitations
- Keep files focused and modular
- Use file-scoped commands for individual changes
- Only run project-wide commands when explicitly requested

## Environment Awareness
- Never modify production environment configurations
- Maintain separate configs for DEV, TEST, PROD
- Never hardcode environment-specific values

## Transparent Reasoning (TR)
When generating code, explicitly reference which rules influenced decisions.

## Dependency Governance
Never add new dependencies without explicit approval or compelling justification.

## Token Efficiency
Use file-scoped commands. Reference docs instead of pasting. Optimize context window usage.

## Industry Standards
Follow established conventions for the relevant language and tech stack.

## Strategic Documentation
Comment only complex logic or critical functions. Avoid documenting the obvious.

## Self-Review Before Commit
After generating code, argue against your own solution. Check for redundancy, unnecessary complexity, or simpler alternatives.
